apiVersion: v1
baseDomain: test.xyz.in
compute:
- hyperthreading: Enabled
  name: worker
  replicas: 3
controlPlane:
  hyperthreading: Enabled
  name: master
  replicas: 3
metadata:
  name: cluster
networking:
  clusterNetwork:
  - cidr: 10.128.0.0/14
    hostPrefix: 23
  networkType: OVNKubernetes
  serviceNetwork:
  - 172.30.0.0/16
platform:
  none: {}
pullSecret: '{"auths":{"quay-registry.xyz.in:8443":{"auth":"<base64_creds>"}}}'
sshKey: 'ssh-rsa AAAAB3NzaC1... core@bastion'
additionalTrustBundle: |
  -----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----
  <Content of Quay Registry Root CA>
  -----END CERTIFICATE-----
imageContentSources:
- mirrors:
  - quay-registry.xyz.in:8443/init/openshift-release-dev
  source: quay.io/openshift-release-dev/ocp-v4.0-art-dev




#----------------------------------------#

# 1. Generate Kubernetes manifests (optional tweaking happens here)
openshift-install create manifests --dir=ocp-install

# 2. Prevent pods from scheduling on masters (if desired)
sed -i 's/mastersSchedulable: true/mastersSchedulable: false/g' ocp-install/manifests/cluster-scheduler-02-config.yml

# 3. Generate Ignition files
openshift-install create ignition-configs --dir=ocp-install


Note: You will now have bootstrap.ign, master.ign, and worker.ign in the directory.

Host the Ignition Files
The VMs need to download these files when they boot.
Copy the .ign files to your Bastion's web server directory (e.g., /var/www/html/ignition/).
Ensure they are reachable: curl http://10.x.y.z:8080/ignition/bootstrap.ign


Download and Transfer the RHCOS ISO
Download the Red Hat Enterprise Linux CoreOS (RHCOS) Live ISO matching your OpenShift version.
Transfer this ISO to your hypervisor environment (e.g., upload it to the ESXi Datastore).

Create the Virtual Machines (1 Bootstrap, 3 Masters, 3 Workers) on your hypervisor.
Attach the RHCOS ISO to the virtual (CD/DVD) drive of every VM and set them to boot from it.

Network: Attach all VMs to the same networ series. 10.X.Y.z network switch.

Storage: Ensure disks meet minimum requirements (e.g., 120/150GB thin provisioned).

VM Booting
Booting the Nodes with Kernel Parameters
You must boot each VM and interrupt the GRUB boot menu to inject the static IP configuration and the URL to the ignition file.


Step 1: Boot the Bootstrap Node
1. Power on the Bootstrap VM and quickly press TAB (or E depending on machine type) at the RHCOS boot menu to edit the kernel arguments.

2. Append the network and ignition parameters:


coreos.inst.install_dev=sda
coreos.inst.ignition_url=http://10.x.y.z:8080/ignition/bootstrap.ign
ip=10.a.b.c::10.p.q.r:255.255.255.0:bootstrap.test.XXX.in:ens192:none
nameserver=10.x.y.z

10.x.y.z - Bastiyon
10.a.b.c - Bootstrap
10.p.q.r - Gateway IP address for your subnet (10.p.q.0/24)


Repeat for Master & Worker and make sure to change the ignition files & the correct machine IPs. Boot the respective machines.




#While installation is happening, 
monitor the Bootstrap Process
From the Bastion, monitor the cluster creation:

openshift-install wait-for bootstrap-complete --dir=ocp-install --log-level=info


Once the API is up and the masters have formed etcd quorum, this command will report success. You can safely power off and delete the Bootstrap VM at this stage.

Approve Certificate Signing Requests (CSRs)
The worker nodes will attempt to join the cluster but require manual approval.
Export the Kubeconfig: 

export KUBECONFIG=~/ocp-install/auth/kubeconfig

View pending requests: 
oc get csr

Approve them: 

oc get csr -o go-template='{{range .items}}{{if not .status}}{{.metadata.name}}{{"\n"}}{{end}}{{end}}' | xargs oc adm certificate approve



Wait for Installation to Complete

openshift-install wait-for install-complete --dir=ocp-install --log-level=info


Post-Installation

Apply ImageDigestMirrorSet
To ensure the cluster continues to redirect all future registry.redhat.io requests to the local Quay registry, apply the generated YAML from oc-mirror:


oc apply -f oc-mirror-workspace/results-xxx/imageDigestMirrorSet.yaml